<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="2e7eab89-54c4-5428-aba0-31cb77eb3796" activityNameId="9f725ae8-16d3-5d27-a04a-a990e3a9ba4e" parentActivityId="ce667afe-c105-5497-b560-70bb53ff6dbd" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">aluminium chloride production</activityName>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Trichloroaluminum</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Trichloroalumane</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Aluminium trichloride</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Pearsall</synonym>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">The activity starts when the raw materials enter the process.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">Materials entering the process are included as well as energy uses, infrastructure and emissions.</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset represents the production of 1 kg of aluminium chloride from the reaction of aluminium melt and hot chlorine gas at high temperatures.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">Aluminium chloride can be produced by the reaction of aluminium with chlorine gas and of aluminium or aluminium hydrozide with hydrochloric acid (Lee et al. 2011 and Helmboldt et al. 2007). This product is used to derive aluminium powder which is used in the fabrication of solar cells and electromagnetic fields (Lee et al. 2011). Aluminium chloride is also “[…] widely applied as acid catalyst, isomerization of hydrocarbon, catalyst of aldehyde synthesis, and catalyst of cation polymerization. In case of an anhydride, it is also used for cracking of oil, and catalyst of Friedel-Crafts reaction in an organic synthesis” (Lee et al. 2011, pp. 40).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">The final product has usually a shading of yellow and gray caused by residues of the reactants. The pure product would instead have a white colour (Helmboldt 2007). Anhydrous aluminium chloride is a hydroscopic, solid that reacts with moisture and air. Aluminium chloride is soluble in chlorinated solvents, while it forms a complex when being dissolved in polar aprotic solvents (Kirk et al. 2004).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">In this dataset, the raw material inputs, and process-specific material exchanges, are modelled with a generic stoichiometry-based tool, using literature or estimated yields. The emissions are modelled with a default value, which is estimated  based on losses, unreacted chemicals, among others. The auxiliary (i.e., cooling water and infrastructure) and energy consumption exchanges are modelled with a default value based on industry data from literature sources.   For more information on the calculations refer to the sampling procedure.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Reference(s):</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Lee, D. et al. 2011. CHEMICAL SYNTHESIS OF ALUMINUM CHLORIDE (AlCl3) BY COST-EFFECTIVE REDUCTION PROCESS. Rev.Adv.Mater. Sci. 28, pp.40-43</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Helmboldt, O. et al. 2007. Aluminum Compounds, Inorganic. In Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry, Electronic Release, Vol.2, pp.569-584. Wiley-VCH, Weinheim.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Kirk, Raymond E., Donald F. Othmer, and Charles A. Mann. "Encyclopedia of Chemical Technology." 2004.</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="28f738cc-bb73-48f8-b633-f83fb9bc5ddc">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">2011:Manufacture of basic chemicals</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="34dbbff8-88ce-11de-ad60-0019e336be3a">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">GLO</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The inventory is modelled at the Global level. The main material inputs and outputs of this activity are generated with on a generic stoichiometry-based model, using literature or estimated yields.  Furthermore, the source of information for the heat, electricity, water (process and cooling), nitrogen, chemical factory is industry data from the GENDORF Chemical Park, which is based in Germany and produced an average of 2462760 tonnes of chemical substances in the years 2015-2019. For more information on the calculations refer to the sampling procedure. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">The dataset could also be considered as not geography-specific, and thus, valid for a broader geographical coverage.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">Hischier, R. (2005) Establishing Life Cycle Inventories of Chemicals Based on Differing Data Availability (9 pp). The International Journal of Life Cycle Assessment, Volume 10, Issue 1, pp 59-67. 10.1065/lca2004.10.181.7 </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2016, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2017, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2020, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit </text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">In the past years the most common method of production of aluminium chloride have been the reaction of aluminium and chlorine gas at high temperatures (Lee et al. 2011 and Helmboldt 2007). Notably, the alluminum could be sourced as a scrap, secondary ingot or prime ingot (Kirk et al. 2004). Chlorine gas is blown in baths of aluminium melt using cylindrical reactors with ceramic lining (Lee et al. 2011 and Helmboldt 2007). This reaction is exothermic with a heat delta of 1.41 MJ/mol, the reaction requires temperatures between 670 to 850 degrees Celsius.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">Chemical reaction:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">2Al + 3Cl2 -&gt; 2AlCl3</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">The product sublimes through the melt pool and subsequently condenses into a vessel where it also solidifies on the condenser walls. The generated crystals of aluminium chloride are periodically removed, processed, and packed under a dry air or nitrogen atmosphere (Kirk et al. 2004). The hot gas that exits the melt pool is filtered to remove entrained liquids and solids, while the off-gases are purified before recycling.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">In this dataset, a yield of 95% was assumed, with a 95% recirculation for the remaining 5% of unreacted aluminium. Finally, the residual alluminium was assumed to be sent for landfill.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Reference(s):</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Lee, D. et al. 2011. CHEMICAL SYNTHESIS OF ALUMINUM CHLORIDE (AlCl3) BY COST-EFFECTIVE REDUCTION PROCESS. Rev.Adv.Mater. Sci. 28, pp.40-43</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Helmboldt, O. et al. 2007. Aluminum Compounds, Inorganic. In Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry, Electronic Release, Vol.2, pp.569-584. Wiley-VCH, Weinheim.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Kirk, Raymond E., Donald F. Othmer, and Charles A. Mann. "Encyclopedia of Chemical Technology." 2004.</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="2015-01-01" endDate="2023-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">In the past years the most common method of production of aluminium chloride have been the reaction of aluminium and chlorine gas at high temperatures (Lee et al. 2011 and Helmboldt 2007).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">The time period spans from the earliest year from which at least one of the input values was obtained until 2020, but overall form the most realistic picture of the production. Besides, the activity is partly generated, in terms of material inputs and outputs, based on a generic stoichiometry-based model, using literature or estimated yields, which does not expect to change over time.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">The source of information for the heat, electricity, water (process and cooling), nitrogen, chemical factory is industry data from the GENDORF Chemical Park. The values are a 5-year average of data from 2015 to 2019 published by the GENDORF Chemical Park, which is based in Germany and produced an average of 2462760 tonnes of chemical substances in the years 2015-2019. The end time period is therefore set based on the years from Gendorf reference.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">For more information on the calculations refer to the sampling procedure and in the comments of the exchanges.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Reference(s):</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Lee, D. et al. 2011. CHEMICAL SYNTHESIS OF ALUMINUM CHLORIDE (AlCl3) BY COST-EFFECTIVE REDUCTION PROCESS. Rev.Adv.Mater. Sci. 28, pp.40-43</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Helmboldt, O. et al. 2007. Aluminum Compounds, Inorganic. In Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry, Electronic Release, Vol.2, pp.569-584. Wiley-VCH, Weinheim.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Hischier, R. (2005) Establishing Life Cycle Inventories of Chemicals Based on Differing Data Availability (9 pp). The International Journal of Life Cycle Assessment, Volume 10, Issue 1, pp 59-67. 10.1065/lca2004.10.181.7 </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2016, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="9">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2017, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="10">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2020, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit </text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
