      <intermediateExchange id="b69297ca-e661-51b3-8253-2c9e21b314f9" unitId="487df68b-4994-4027-8fdc-a4dc298257b7" casNumber="007429-90-5" amount="0.15763873078548943" isCalculatedAmount="true" mathematicalRelation="0.213-(0.0475*0.213)" intermediateExchangeId="44defed2-3dc7-4d59-b3bc-23dacf1b9140" activityLinkId="c11535fc-c215-5be2-beab-c9d3e606567a">
        <name xml:lang="en">aluminium, primary, ingot</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">kg</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">Calculated value based on stoichiometric calculations and literature data. 26.981539g/mol is the molar mass of aluminium, primary, liquid (Al). 133.339639g/mol is the molar mass of aluminium chloride (AlCl3). In the past years the most common method of production of aluminium chloride have been the reaction of aluminium and chlorine gas at high temperatures (Lee et al. 2011 and Helmboldt 2007). Chlorine gas is blown in baths of aluminium using cylindrical reactors with ceramic lining (Lee et al. 2011 and Helmboldt 2007). This reaction is exothermic with a heat delta of 1.41 MJ/mol, the reaction requires temperatures between 670 to 850 degrees Celsius. Chemical reaction: 2Al + 3Cl2 -&gt; 2AlCl3 With a yield of 95%, 0.213 kg of aluminium is necessary. Of the remaing 5%, recirculation of 95% was assumed (equals 4.75% of entire input), therefore it was subtracted from the input. The remaining 5% (0.25% of entire input) was sent to landfill.</comment>
        <uncertainty>
          <lognormal meanValue="0.15763873078548943" mu="-1.8474493780358217" variance="0.0006" varianceWithPedigreeUncertainty="0.010025"/>
          <pedigreeMatrix reliability="2" completeness="3" temporalCorrelation="2" geographicalCorrelation="2" furtherTechnologyCorrelation="3"/>
        </uncertainty>
